excerpt: Cooperative-owned shopping quarter with independent boutiques, galleries, restaurants & a theatre.
detail_description: Nestled in the old ports district, Quartier Petit Champlain is a cooperative-owned shopping quarter featuring independent boutiques, galleries, restaurants, and a theater. This historic area is renowned as the oldest commercial district in North America and has been a hub for craftsmen, merchants, and artists for generations. The pedestrian-only streets are popular year-round, offering a charming atmosphere with snow-capped structures during the ski season and authentic French restaurants serving local delicacies and ice wine.
name: Quartier Petit Champlain
address: 61 Rue du Petit Champlain, Québec City, Quebec G1K 4H5, Canada

excerpt: Set in a historic park, this battle site in the Seven Years' War features gardens & an ice rink.
detail_description: The Plains of Abraham is a historic park in Quebec, Canada, known for its pivotal role in the Seven Years' War. This urban park was the site of the famous Battle of Quebec in 1759, where British forces defeated the French. The park features gardens, an ice rink, and Martello Towers with family-friendly activities. Visitors can explore the Museum of the Plains of Abraham to learn about Canada's history through multimedia displays.
name: Plains of Abraham
address: 835 Wilfrid-Laurier Ave, Québec City, Quebec G1R 2L3, Canada

excerpt: Dating to 1647, this opulent church has been rebuilt a few times & features a historic crypt.
detail_description: Notre-Dame de Québec Basilica-Cathedral, dating back to 1647, has undergone several reconstructions and boasts a historic crypt. The cathedral's rich history is reflected in its opulent interior adorned with impressive works of art, including an Episcopal throne canopy, stained glass, paintings, sculptures, and a sanctuary lamp from Louis XIV. The site also houses the tombs of governors of New France and many bishops of Quebec City.
name: Notre-Dame de Québec Basilica-Cathedral
address: 16 Rue De Buade, Québec City, Quebec G1R 4A1, Canada

excerpt: Towering waterfall with scenic views from trails, steps, a suspension bridge & a tram.
detail_description: Montmorency Falls, located just a short distance from Quebec City, is an awe-inspiring natural attraction standing at 83 meters tall, even higher than Niagara Falls. Visitors can enjoy various activities year-round, such as hiking in the summer and ice climbing in the winter. The falls are easily accessible by car or bike and offer stunning views from different vantage points including trails, a suspension bridge, and a tram.
name: Montmorency Falls
address: Québec City, Quebec G1C 2H1, Canada

excerpt: Picturesque cobblestoned square flanked by cafes, shops & a 17th-century stone church.
detail_description: Place Royale in Quebec City, Canada is a charming cobblestoned square surrounded by cafes, shops, and a 17th-century stone church. This historic landmark dates back to the early 17th century and is an integral part of Old Quebec. It was the site where Samuel de Champlain founded the city in 1608. The area is filled with restaurants, coffee shops, and unique places to visit that are rich in history and character.
name: Place Royale
address: 2-4 Rue des Pains Bénits, Ville de Québec, QC G1K Rue des Pains Bénits, Québec City, Quebec G1K 4E9, Canada

excerpt: Québec City sits on the Saint Lawrence River in Canada's mostly French-speaking Québec province. Dating to 1608, it has a fortified colonial core, Vieux-Québec and Place Royale, with stone buildings and narrow streets. This area is the site of the towering Château Frontenac Hotel and imposing Citadelle of Québec. The Petit Champlain district’s cobblestone streets are lined with bistros and boutiques.
detail_description: Québec City, located in Canada's Québec province, is a historic gem dating back to 1608. Its Vieux-Québec and Place Royale areas boast charming stone buildings and narrow streets, including the iconic Château Frontenac Hotel and Citadelle of Québec. The Petit Champlain district offers cobblestone streets lined with quaint bistros and boutiques.
name: Québec City
address: Quebec, Canada

excerpt: Built in 1859, this long, popular terrace overlooking the river also offers scenic city views.
detail_description: Dufferin Terrace, also known as Terrasse Dufferin, is a historic wooden boardwalk built in 1859 that offers stunning views of the Saint Lawrence River, Chateau Frontenac, and the Citadel of Quebec. It is a popular spot for both locals and tourists to enjoy leisurely strolls while taking in panoramic city views. In the winter, visitors can experience the famous Terrasse Dufferin Slides toboggan run during the Quebec Winter Carnival.
name: Dufferin Terrace
address: Rue des Carrières, Québec City, Quebec G1R 5J5, Canada

excerpt: Viewing space on the 31st floor of the Marie-Guyart Building, the city's tallest skyscraper at 132m.
detail_description: The Observatoire de la Capitale, located on the 31st floor of the Marie-Guyart Building, offers a stunning 360-degree view of Quebec City. As the city's tallest skyscraper at 132m, it provides an unparalleled vantage point to admire historic landmarks such as Old Quebec and Cap Diamant, as well as scenic features like the St. Lawrence River and the Louise Basin marina.
name: Observatoire de la Capitale
address: 1037 Rue de la Chevrotière, Québec City, Quebec G1R 5E9, Canada

excerpt: Complex featuring a long-standing active fort, plus a museum & changing of the guard ceremonies.
detail_description: The Citadelle of Québec is a historic complex that includes an active fort, a museum, and the traditional Changing of the Guard ceremony. However, during certain times of the year, this ceremony is replaced by a musical performance by the Royal 22nd Regiment Band. The citadel has been an important part of Quebec's history since it was rebuilt by the British in the 19th century.
name: The Citadelle of Québec
address: 1 Côte de la Citadelle, Québec City, Quebec G1R 3R2, Canada

detail_description: Old Quebec, the historic heart of Quebec City, encompasses both the Upper Town (Haute-Ville) and Lower Town (Basse-Ville) along the St Lawrence River. Enclosed by 2.85 miles of fortifications, it is adorned with historic landmarks and presided over by Chateau Frontenac, a picturesque castle that functions as the city's premier hotel.
name: Old Quebec
address: Québec City, QC, Canada

excerpt: Works by Quebecois artists including Alfred Pellan, plus paintings of Quebec & touring exhibitions.
detail_description: The Musée national des beaux-arts du Québec, located on the vibrant Grand Allee, is a neoclassical museum with a modern wing designed by renowned architects Rem Koolhaas and Shohei Shigematsu. The Lassonde Pavilion, added in 2016, showcases a remarkable collection of 22,000 traditional and contemporary Quebec art pieces.
name: Musée national des beaux-arts du Québec
address: 179 Grande Allée O, Québec City, Quebec G1R 2H1, Canada

excerpt: This Second Empire-style building is home to Quebec's National Assembly & offers free guided tours.
detail_description: The Parliament Building, located in Quebec City's St. Jean Baptiste district, is a stunning Second Empire-style structure surrounded by beautiful gardens. Dating back to the late 19th century, it serves as an important center of politics and offers free guided tours of its well-preserved interior with impressive architecture. The grounds are adorned with numerous monuments and 26 bronze statues that pay homage to key figures in Quebec's political history.
name: Parliament Building
address: 1045 Rue des Parlementaires, Québec City, Quebec G1A 1A3, Canada

excerpt: Former city prison, built in 1808, hosting English-language culture & arts programs & tours.
detail_description: The Morrin Centre, located in Quebec City, is a historic landmark that was originally built as the city's first prison in 1808. Today, it houses the Literary and Historical Society of Quebec and features a vast English-language library with over 20,000 books, archives, manuscripts, films, artifacts, and decorative items related to English families of Quebec City.
name: Morrin Centre
address: 44 Chau. des Écossais, Québec City, Quebec G1R 4H3, Canada

excerpt: Stone church dedicated to St. Genevieve, dating to 1688 & rebuilt in 1763 after the Siege of Quebec.
detail_description: Notre-Dame-des-Victoires Catholic Church is a historic stone church in Quebec City, dedicated to St. Genevieve and boasting a rich history dating back to 1688. The church was rebuilt twice after being destroyed during the Siege of Quebec in 1759 and features unique elements of French Romanesque architecture.
name: Notre-Dame-des-Victoires Catholic Church
address: 32 Rue Sous-le-Fort, Québec City, Quebec G1K 4E8, Canada

excerpt: Indoor & outdoor space with roughly 10,000 animals, including fish, marine mammals & amphibians.
detail_description: Located in the Ste-Foy sector of Quebec City, the Aquarium of Quebec offers a captivating experience for nature enthusiasts. With both indoor and outdoor spaces, visitors can explore approximately 10,000 animals, including fish, marine mammals, and amphibians. The outdoor area features paths through a wetlands ecosystem with close-up views of aquatic plants, birds, amphibians, insects, and reptiles. Additionally, harbor seals can be observed overlooking the St.
name: Aquarium of Quebec
address: 1675 Av. des Hôtels, Québec City, Quebec G1W 4S3, Canada

excerpt: Riverside city park with cable cars & zip lines over a high waterfall, plus via ferrata circuits.
detail_description: Parc de la Chute-Montmorency, located just a short drive from Quebec City, offers a variety of thrilling activities and breathtaking views. Visitors can marvel at the 272-foot Montmorency Falls from different vantage points, including a suspension bridge and observation decks. The park also features cable cars, zip lines over the waterfall, and via ferrata circuits for adventurous souls. Guided tours provide insights into the manor's history and lead to panoramic viewpoints.
name: Parc de la Chute-Montmorency
address: 5300 Bd Sainte-Anne, Québec City, Quebec G1C 0M3, Canada

detail_description: The Fortifications of Québec National Historic Site is a remarkable example of seventeenth-century military architecture and played a crucial role in defending the colony against sieges by the French and Americans. These sturdy ramparts, gates, and towers have been expanded and improved over the centuries, now stretching almost three miles around Old Quebec. As the only remaining city walls in North America outside of Mexico, they are an important part of Canada's history and are well-preserved for visitors to explore.
name: Fortifications of Québec National Historic Site
address: 2 Rue D'Auteuil, Québec City, Quebec G1R 5C2, Canada

detail_description: Nestled along the banks of the St. Lawrence River, the Old City of Quebec is a charming blend of history and culture that captivates every visitor. This UNESCO World Heritage Site boasts beautifully preserved stone buildings and winding streets that transport you back in time. As you stroll through this historic neighborhood, you'll encounter must-see attractions like the Citadel, Quartier Petit-Champlain—one of North America's oldest shopping streets—and the stunning Notre-Dame de Quebec Basilica-Cathedral.
name: Old City of Quebec
address: Rue Hébert, Québec City, Quebec G1R 4K7, Canada

excerpt: Quiet cobblestoned passageway lined with stalls displaying works by a variety of artists.
detail_description: Rue du Trésor, also known as "Artists Street," is a charming cobblestoned passageway in Quebec City. Its name originates from the former royal treasury that once stood nearby during the French Regime. Today, it serves as an open-air art gallery where local artists gather to display their works, creating a vibrant and atmospheric setting.
name: Rue du Trésor
address: Québec, QC, Canada

excerpt: Former barracks, prison & foundry, open in summer for guided tours & battle reenactments.
detail_description: Artillery Park is a historical site in Quebec City that offers guided tours and battle reenactments during the summer. The park encompasses various significant structures such as the mills redoubt, Mont-Carmel Park, Esplanade powder magazine, Artillery barracks, and more. It provides insights into the history of French and British troops from 1712 to the end of the 20th century.
name: Artillery Park
address: 2 Rue D'Auteuil, Québec City, Quebec G1R 5C2, Canada

detail_description: Carnaval de Québec, also known as the Quebec Winter Carnival, is a beloved tradition that has been celebrated for over 60 years. This annual event takes place over three weekends in January and February, offering a wide array of activities such as sports, family-friendly events, and vibrant celebrations. The festival features night parades, giant games, gourmet experiences, and colorful challenges that light up Quebec City.
name: Carnaval de Québec
address: 205 Bd des Cèdres, Québec, QC G1N1L8, Canada

excerpt: Public meadows & trees covering 103 hectares & site of a 1759 battle between the French & British.
detail_description: The Battlefields Park, also known as Parc des Champs-de-Bataille, spans 267 acres and was the site of a significant battle between French and British forces in 1759. The park features public meadows, trees, and monuments commemorating the historic clash. Today, it serves as a popular public park with open green spaces used for various events and concerts. Visitors can enjoy picnics, recreational areas, and stunning views of the St.
name: The Battlefields Park
address: 835 Wilfrid-Laurier Ave, Québec City, Quebec G1R 2L3, Canada

excerpt: This iconic street with historic architecture, restaurants & bars hosts yearly events & festivities.
detail_description: Grande Allée is an iconic street known for its historic architecture, vibrant atmosphere, and a variety of restaurants and bars. It hosts annual events and is a popular spot for tourists from around the world. The area is easily explorable on foot, encompassing main neighborhoods like Vieux-Quebec, Petit-Champlain, Place-Royale, Vieux-Port, Montcalm, and Saint-Jean-Baptiste.
name: Grande Allée
address: Québec, QC, Canada

excerpt: An animated diorama show depicts the city's historic military battles at this quaint museum.
detail_description: The Fort Museum, also known as Musee du Fort, is a quaint museum in Quebec City that offers a 30-minute multimedia exhibition showcasing the city's historic military battles. Through visual demonstrations and sound and light effects, visitors can immerse themselves in key events such as the battle on the Plains of Abraham and Benedict Arnold's march to Quebec City. The museum provides an entertaining and educational experience for families, making it a must-visit to understand the city's history.
name: The Fort Museum
address: 10 Rue Sainte-Anne, Québec City, Quebec G1R 4S7, Canada

excerpt:
Lévis is a city in eastern Quebec, Canada, located on the south shore of the St. Lawrence River, opposite Quebec City. A ferry links Old Quebec with Old Lévis, and two bridges, the Quebec Bridge and the Pierre-Laporte Bridge, connect western Lévis with Quebec City.
The population in 2021 was 149,683. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Lévis, situated on the southern bank of the St. Lawrence River in Quebec, Canada, is a charming city with a population of around 149,683. It is connected to Quebec City by a ferry and two bridges - the Quebec Bridge and the Pierre-Laporte Bridge. The ferry ride offers stunning views of both cities and is an excellent opportunity for photography enthusiasts.
name: Levis
address: Quebec, Canada

excerpt: Quaint, narrow pedestrian street lined with restaurants, cafes & boutiques in elegant buildings.
detail_description: Rue du Petit Champlain is a charming, narrow pedestrian street located at the base of Cape Diamond in Quebec City. It is the heart of a quaint neighborhood that pays homage to Samuel de Champlain, the founder of Quebec City. This historic area is known for its old-world charm, with cozy cafes, quaint shops, and elegant buildings lining the cobblestone street.
name: Rue du Petit Champlain
address: Québec, QC, Canada

excerpt: Established thoroughfare passing through an old city gate featuring restaurants, shops & landmarks.
detail_description: Rue Saint-Jean is a historic thoroughfare that runs through an old city gate and is lined with a variety of dining, shopping, and notable landmarks. The street offers a vibrant atmosphere with trendy shops, bars, and restaurants as well as interesting architectural features. Visitors can also explore the quieter side streets in the area.
name: Rue Saint-Jean
address: Québec, QC, Canada

excerpt: Wendake is the current name for two urban reserves, Wendake 7 and Wendake 7A, of the Huron-Wendat Nation in the Canadian province of Quebec. They are enclaves entirely surrounded by the La Haute-Saint-Charles borough of Quebec City, within the former city of Loretteville. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Wendake, located in the Canadian province of Quebec, is home to two urban reserves of the Huron-Wendat Nation. These enclaves are surrounded by the La Haute-Saint-Charles borough of Quebec City. The area offers a rich culinary scene, with restaurants like La Traite and Melba showcasing traditional herbs and seasonal local ingredients.
name: Wendake
address: Quebec G2A 3Z6, Canada

excerpt: Home of the city's congress centre and the Grand Théâtre de Québec, this buzzing downtown neighbourhood is dotted with colourful houses and historic buildings such as the Saint-Jean-Baptiste Church. Quirky book and record shops add a bohemian air around Rue Saint-Jean, which draws tourists to its cozy bistros, boutiques, cafes and cake shops. Several watering holes offer live music, and many cater to a gay clientele.
detail_description: Saint-Jean-Baptiste is a lively downtown neighborhood in Quebec City, known for its vibrant atmosphere and historic charm. The area is home to the city's congress center, the Grand Théâtre de Québec, and the iconic Saint-Jean-Baptiste Church. Visitors can explore colorful houses, quirky book and record shops along Rue Saint-Jean, as well as cozy bistros, boutiques, cafes, and cake shops.
name: Saint-Jean-Baptiste
address: Québec City, QC, Canada

excerpt: Cycling & walking path along the St. Lawrence River, with play areas for kids in the waterside park.
detail_description: Promenade Samuel-De Champlain is a picturesque 2.7-mile park along the St. Lawrence River, offering unobstructed views of the river and a perfect spot for picnics and sunset watching. The park features play areas for kids, sports facilities, and four distinct sections: wetlands with waterslide access, a lookout point, sports fields, and a cultural focal point. It's an ideal place for walking, running or cycling by the water's edge.
name: Promenade Samuel-De Champlain
address: 2795 Bd Champlain, Québec City, Quebec G1T 1X9, Canada

excerpt: Exhibits on ancient & current world societies, including First Nations, New France & modern Quebec.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Old Quebec, the Museum of Civilization stands as a vibrant testament to human history and culture. Overlooking the picturesque port, this architectural marvel designed by Moshe Safdie invites visitors to delve into both ancient and contemporary societies. Its permanent exhibition, "This is Story," highlights the rich heritage of Indigenous nations in Quebec, showcasing an impressive array of artifacts that celebrate their traditions and contributions.
name: Museum of Civilization
address: 85 Rue Dalhousie, Québec City, Quebec G1K 8R2, Canada

excerpt: Saint-Roch is a hip district with lots of small restaurants, cafes, and lively bars, as well as boutiques selling clothes, housewares, and toys, along Rue Saint-Joseph. Music venues, theaters, and contemporary art galleries dot the entire area. The Jardin Jean-Paul L’Allier features gardens and a man-made waterfall, and nearby is the towering Église Saint-Roch. The city’s pro baseball team plays at Stade CANAC.
detail_description: Saint-Roch is a vibrant district filled with an array of small eateries, cafes, and lively bars. The area also boasts trendy boutiques offering a variety of goods along Rue Saint-Joseph. Visitors can explore music venues, theaters, and contemporary art galleries throughout the neighborhood. Additionally, the Jardin Jean-Paul L’Allier showcases beautiful gardens and a man-made waterfall while the towering Église Saint-Roch stands nearby.
name: Saint-Roch
address: Québec City, QC, Canada

excerpt: Flanked by Plains of Abraham Park along the St. Lawrence River, Montcalm is known as the arts district due to its theatres, the Musée national des beaux-arts du Québec, and its close proximity to both the opera and symphony. It’s primarily a residential area dotted with cafes, restaurants, and upscale shops along Avenue Cartier. There's also a busy nightlife and the 1850s Maison Henry-Stuart museum along Grand Allee.
detail_description: Montcalm, located along the St. Lawrence River and adjacent to Plains of Abraham Park, is renowned for its vibrant arts scene. The neighborhood houses several theaters, the Musée national des beaux-arts du Québec, and is in close proximity to the opera and symphony. Montcalm is primarily a residential area with charming cafes, restaurants, and upscale shops lining Avenue Cartier. At night, the district comes alive with its bustling nightlife.
name: Montcalm
address: Québec City, QC, Canada

detail_description: Nestled in the charming Upper Town of Quebec City, the Cathedral of the Holy Trinity holds a significant place in history as the first Anglican cathedral established outside of the British Isles. Constructed between 1800 and 1804, this architectural gem showcases a dignified facade that echoes London's St. Martin-in-the-Fields, featuring Palladian elements like Ionic pilasters and an elegant pediment.
name: Cathedral of the Holy Trinity
address: 31 Rue des Jardins, Québec City, Quebec G1R 4L6, Canada

excerpt: Archaeological remains of 4 forts & châteaux dating from 1620–1694, with guided tours in English.
detail_description: Saint-Louis Forts and Châteaux National Historic Site offers a fascinating journey through the archaeological remains of four forts and châteaux dating back to 1620–1694. Managed by Parks Canada, this site provides guided tours in English, allowing visitors to explore the underground treasures beneath Terrasse Dufferin.
name: Saint-Louis Forts and Châteaux National Historic Site
address: Dufferin Terrace, Québec City, Quebec G1R 6C7, Canada

excerpt: This large urban space surrounded by historic structures is home to an ice skating rink in winter.
detail_description: Place D'Youville is a bustling urban space located at a significant junction in the city, serving as a cultural hub between Old Quebec and the Quebec Parliament Hill. It has historical significance dating back to the 1730s and was once an important market square. The area is surrounded by historic structures and is home to an ice skating rink in winter, offering a picturesque backdrop of Old Quebec. Additionally, it houses several cultural institutions nearby and serves as a gathering place with its rich history.
name: Place D'Youville
address: Rue Saint-Jean, Québec City, Quebec G1R 6E2, Canada

excerpt: Landscaped plaza on the St. Lawrence River with lawns & walkways, plus a fountain & splash pad.
detail_description: Nestled along the picturesque St. Lawrence River, Place des Canotiers is a beautifully landscaped plaza that invites visitors to unwind and soak in the stunning views of Old Quebec City. This vibrant public square features lush lawns, charming walkways, and a delightful fountain with water jets perfect for cooling off during warm summer days. The area is particularly enchanting in the fall when the foliage transforms into a tapestry of colors.
name: Place des Canotiers
address: 40 Rue Dalhousie, Québec, QC G1K 4B2, Canada

excerpt: Outdoor recreational complex featuring waterslides & a wave pool in summer & wintertime activities.
detail_description: Valcartier Vacation Village, located about 20 miles northeast of Old Quebec near the Jacques-Cartier River, is a popular all-season resort offering a wide range of activities. Originally known for its toboggan run and snow tubing, the resort now features water slides and pools in the summer, as well as winter activities such as snow tubing and ice skating.
name: Valcartier Vacation Village
address: 2280 Bd Valcartier, Saint-Gabriel-de-Valcartier, Quebec G0A 4S0, Canada

excerpt: Petite restaurant with a warm ambience & outdoor seating serving French fare & weekend brunch.
detail_description: Le Lapin Sauté is a charming restaurant with a cozy atmosphere and outdoor seating, offering a delightful selection of French cuisine with a Quebecois twist. The menu features an array of rabbit dishes, including the popular rabbit poutine and warm rabbit liver salad, all made from naturally farmed rabbits. In addition to rabbit specialties, the restaurant also offers decadent options like cured duck sharing platters and gourmet grilled cheese sandwiches.
name: Le Lapin Sauté
address: 52 Rue du Petit Champlain, Québec City, Quebec G1K 4H4, Canada

excerpt: Artsy brewpub featuring simple fare like burgers & organic meat plates & their brand of craft beers.
detail_description: La Korrigane - Brasserie artisanale is an artsy brewpub in Quebec City that offers a simple menu featuring burgers and organic meat plates alongside their own craft beers. Since 2010, this women-owned brewery has been dedicated to crafting beer using traditional artisanal methods and promoting Quebec-based micro-enterprises while using local ingredients for both their beer and food menus.
name: La Korrigane - Brasserie artisanale
address: 380 Rue Dorchester, Québec, QC G1K 6A7, Canada

detail_description: Paillard is a charming bakery located on Rue Saint-Jean in Quebec City, offering a warm and inviting atmosphere with long communal tables. It has become a favorite spot for both locals and visitors, providing a place to experience the daily rhythm of the city. The cafe offers an array of homemade delicacies, from coffee and croissants to fresh salads and sandwiches that rival the best boulangeries in France.
name: Paillard
address: 1097 Rue Saint-Jean, Québec City, Quebec G1R 1S3, Canada

excerpt: Refined rotating restaurant atop Hôtel le Concorde offering elevated bistro fare & bird's-eye views.
detail_description: Ciel! Bistro-bar is a unique dining experience located on the 28th floor of Hôtel le Concorde in Quebec City. It offers breathtaking panoramic views of Old Quebec City, Grande-Allee, the Plains of Abraham, and the St. Lawrence River as it slowly revolves. The restaurant features a refined menu with locally-sourced dishes such as tomato tartlet with fresh mozzarella and organic chicken ballotine.
name: Ciel! Bistro-bar
address: 1225 Cr du Général de Montcalm, Québec, QC G1R 4W6, Canada

excerpt: Christmas ornaments, lights, tree-toppers & more displayed in a festive shop open all year.
detail_description: La Boutique de Noël de Québec is a year-round Christmas shop located in Quebec City, offering a festive atmosphere with Christmas ornaments, lights, and tree-toppers. The city itself becomes magical during the holiday season, but this shop allows visitors to take home a piece of that spirit any time of year. The shop is situated at various locations throughout the city, including Rue du Petit-Champlain and inside the Chateau Frontenac.
name: La Boutique de Noël de Québec
address: 47 Rue De Buade, Québec City, Quebec G1R 4A2, Canada

excerpt: Restaurant serving upmarket, seasonal Nordic bistro fare in a stylish, modern interior.
detail_description: Chez Boulay-bistro boréal offers an upscale dining experience with a stylish, modern interior. Renowned chefs Jean-Luc Boulay and Arnaud Marchand create elegant interpretations of northern Quebec cuisine using entirely local ingredients. The menu features reinvented classic desserts and dishes such as bison tartare, braised beef ravioli, and salmon in cranberry glaze.
name: Chez Boulay-bistro boréal
address: 1110 Rue Saint-Jean, Québec City, Quebec G1R 1S4, Canada

detail_description: Montmorency Falls Parking is located about 9 miles northeast of Old Quebec along the St. Lawrence River, and it's a popular destination for nature lovers and sightseers. The 272-foot waterfall is one-and-a-half times taller than Niagara Falls, making it a breathtaking natural wonder. While summer offers more comfortable temperatures, some travelers recommend visiting in winter to enjoy the beauty without the crowds. The park surrounding the falls provides scenic views and well-planned trails for exploration.
name: Montmorency Falls Parking
address: Unnamed Road, Boischatel, Quebec G0A 1H0, Canada

detail_description: Laurie Raphaël in Quebec City offers a luxurious dining experience with its opulent set menus featuring 3-13 dishes and optional wine pairings. The restaurant presents five distinct epicurean themes, including New Arrival, Heritage and Traditions, Cuisines and Classics, The Flavour Transmission, and The Seasons Mark.
name: Laurie Raphaël, Quebec City
address: 117 Rue Dalhousie, Québec City, Quebec G1K 9C8, Canada

detail_description: Chez Ashton is a renowned Quebec establishment known for serving traditional poutine. It originated as a fries truck in 1969 and expanded to its first permanent location in 1976. While it's considered one of the best spots for poutine, some find it slightly pricey. The restaurant also offers tasty burgers, but their poutines are the real highlight. Visitors praise the quality of the cheese curds, flavorful sauce, and crispy fries.
name: Chez Ashton
address: 600 Rue du Marais, Québec City, Quebec G1M 3R1, Canada

excerpt: Relaxed mini-chain venue offering build-your-own poutine with upmarket toppings & diner fare.
detail_description: Restaurant Poutineville Saint-Roch is a relaxed venue that offers a unique twist on the classic Quebec dish, poutine. While it's true that Quebec cuisine is not just about poutine and maple syrup, this restaurant provides an opportunity to indulge in these delicacies with a gourmet touch.
name: Restaurant Poutineville Saint-Roch
address: 735 Rue Saint-Joseph E, Québec City, Quebec G1K 3C6, Canada

detail_description: Cap Diamant, also known as Cape Diamond, offers breathtaking views of the Saint Lawrence River, Dufferin Terrace, and the city of Quebec. The promontory is home to iconic landmarks such as Chateau Frontenac and the Citadel of Quebec. Walking through old Quebec reveals the enormous rock on which these historic structures are built. The area's peaceful atmosphere and inclusive people make it a truly pleasant experience.
name: Cap Diamant
address: Levis, QC, Canada

detail_description: Petit-Champlain is a charming pedestrian street filled with local shops and an enchanting ambiance. It's known for its concentration of art galleries and fine bistros, making it a bona fide memory maker. This area offers a taste of Europe in North America, with splendid and romantic surroundings that are a must-see. Visitors can also enjoy Tintin ice sculptures while exploring this corner of arts and artists.
name: Petit-Champlain
address: Québec, QC G1K 4H4, Canada
